snippet.textDisplay: I am from south india (Hyderabad,precisely), but have lived in delhi, bangalore and bombay for sometime. I have also lived in london (along with some pakistani friends). During these years, i have made friends from pakistan, delhi, and punjab, who speak punjabi language and have a punjabi lineage. I have fell in love with the language and the punjabi culture. Despite the fact that i keep failing in learning the language, i keep listening to coke studio pakistan (punjabi songs, precisely). This song brings a lot of happiness and joy, and it keeps proving that music can unite anyone despite their backgrounds, religions and creeds. I personally love nabeel's voice, ali sethi has given the song its eliteness. This is just awesome. I love you pakistan, more than that, i love the musicians' from your country.  Peace be persist across the nations.

snippet.textDisplay:
A beautiful  kalam sung in a beautiful way. Both the singers have done justice to the depth of meaning that the lyrics carry. A friend  has suggested that it should have been sung by female singers because the feelings expressed in the lyrics are those of a female. He needs to be told that in Sufi poetry the beloved is God, who is addressed as male and Sufi poets consider themselves as female in the expression of their love for him. 
      Umran Langham pabban bar,  a Jay na was a toon kali a. ..... ( I have spent ages in waiting for you to shower your blessings, o my beloved. kalia literally means 'o black'. The Essence of God is Black an his attributes are white with all the colours in it. Dark clouds carry rain that is taken as a revelation or tajalli of God. The lovers of God keep waiting for  His revelations  an when they do not get His attention, they cry out: " you have maddened me and then left me alone to roam around in the streets, like a koonj ( crane) that cries after separation from its flock."  wangan or the bangles  have a jingle that intoxicates the lovers. They are colourful and add to the beauty of brides. Their jingle reveal the presence of their wearer, who go around carrying the memory of the beloved who has gifted them. These lyrics reflect a different spiritual state...a state of union with the beloved. Umran langhian is a song of separation ....while Ali Sethi cries out in a state of separation from the beloved, Nabeel celebrates union. .........this is what makes this song unique.   ..... I love this combination. They have combined the beauty of Asad Amanat Ali's song of pain with Loonewala's song of joy.
